It’s sadly our last week of celebrating and learning lessons from amazing women of history - but no doubt we are ending on a high. At allWomen, we are a little too familiar with the isolation women experience in the world of tech, as they enter a space that was not built with them in mind. But luckily, we follow in the footsteps of brilliant women who have paved the way for more smart ladies to help build better, more inclusive technology. And we’d like to spend today honoring one of the most badassiest of ladies in tech, our Artificial Intelligence hero: Regina Llopis.

Originally born in Venezuela, Regina has spent a lot of her life around the world studying, teaching, and using her background in applied mathematics to create captivating artificial intelligence. (For example, she built a tool that predicts musical hits, cause she’s what? A BADASS)

But she’s never been interested in creating any-old algorithm. Rather, she’s endlessly inspired by what algorithms can do to help people. And, perhaps more importantly, she’s focused on what they can do to unintentionally hurt people if they’re not created carefully and ethnically. This passion for bettering the world through AI informed much of her life and is what makes her so inspiring and important to the world of tech. #AIGoals amiright?

She was so driven by this idea that she helped found Aplicaciones en Informática Avanzada with the intention of “building algorithms for a better world.” To this day, AIA continues to develop innovative solutions for companies facing challenging problems thanks to a unique method based on the diversity of thought. Yes Regina, we see you!

In our eyes, Regina is the perfect tech role model because her work has taught us so much about creating ethical machine-learning technology that can be used for the greater good. It’s something that we see our students aspire to and we believe it to be one of the best things that women are bringing to tech: a more global view of what technology can be and how it can help diverse communities around the world. 

So if you ever feel like you don’t belong in the world of tech, let’s prove this stereotype wrong - the Regina Llopis way!

PART 2. “Shadow Play: Tales of Urbanization in China” project by @lily_honglei 
•

Lily & Honglei’s projects explore the new significance of art in the digital age. They examine postdigital visual culture by raising questions about apparent dichotomies such as form and narrative as well as traditional media and digital technology. These inquiries revolve
around the theme of the inclusiveness of the postdigital, and consider the implications for the creative power of artists and the efficacy of artworks. 

The Shadow Play project commenced in 2014 with the objective of digitally visualizing the artists’ investigation into a complex socio-economic reality - the process of relentless urbanization in China -, by portraying the city as a gigantic maze with no exit.
The product, which is a culmination of several years of experimentation, integrates thoroughly-researched narrative storytelling with the sensory capabilities of virtual reality (VR) and augmented reality (AR) technologies.
Over the trajectory of its development, the project has grown into a multiplatform project interweaving VR, AR, painting, and Chinese folk art forms. The artists created numerous visual compositions with traditional Chinese shadow puppetry motifs and transplanted them into a 3D virtual world platform, where the main narrative - the tragic tale of the village chief’s family - unfolds. 
Lily & Honglei subsequently produced a series of large-scale paintings that they dub postdigital fine art based on imagery in the virtual world. 

Finally, through their practice in both new media and traditional art forms such as painting and folk media, the artists have come upon a stream of creative vitality that comes forth from exchanges between the two and gives new life to old visual forms.

Shadow Play receives support from New York Foundation for the Arts, New York State Council on the Arts, Queens Council on the Arts, and New Radio and Performing Arts, Inc. It is a recipient of Creative Capital Awards in Visual Arts and New York Foundation for the Arts Fellowship in Interdisciplinary Art, United States
